From: djb@silverton.berkeley.edu (D. J. Bernstein)
Crossposted-To: gnu.misc.discuss
Subject: Re: Creeping featuritis (post --rant --flame)
Date: 1 Dec 93 07:47:20 GMT

In article <CH4osz.LHp@murdoch.acc.Virginia.EDU> gl8f@fermi.clas.Virginia.EDU (Greg Lindahl) writes:
> Or being able to
> compress the archive, have one bit flip in the first volume, and still
> restore most of it.
> You can pick great examples of things that should always be filters,
> but industrial-strength full-featured multi-volume backups isn't it.

I would hope that industrial-strength backups use write checks and
error-correcting codes, so that you can restore _all_ of it, not _most_.
Do you think the writecheck and ecc filters should be part of tar too?

---Dan

------------------------------

From: djb@silverton.berkeley.edu (D. J. Bernstein)
Crossposted-To: gnu.misc.discuss
Subject: Re: Creeping featuritis (post --rant --flame)
Date: 2 Dec 93 10:13:11 GMT

In article <haley.754801944@scws14> haley@scws14.harvard.edu (Elizabeth Haley) writes:
> >The user can replace a big file FOO with a whole bunch of little files
> >FOO/0 FOO/32768 etc. (the numbers indicating byte markers). Why, oh why, 
> >if this feature _had_ to be in tar, wasn't it implemented just like 
> >this?
> Because the feature as you suggest it is annoying and inefficient.

You are confused. What I suggested was a way in which GNU tar's 
multi-volume support could have been _implemented_. How could it be 
any more annoying or inefficient than the existing code? It'd work the
same from the user's point of view---same option, same speed.

The differences are (1) it would require at most twenty lines of code
and (2) it would produce tar files which could be extracted with non-GNU
versions of tar.

(This is of course only a side issue. I was reacting to Mike's comment
about the complexity of GNU tar's multi-volume support. Such complexity
is entirely unnecessary.)

> If
> I am archiving things that I know are larger than the media I am
> writing to, I don't particularly want to make a bunch of small chunks,
> and attempt to figure out where the tape is going to end in relation to
> the chunks when the program can figure out where it ends on the fly
> and make just one break in just one file.

I agree. Certainly, if you want this feature, then you want a program
to do the work for you.

But should it be the tar program? No.

It makes no sense to load down tar and cpio and pax and zip and zoo and
so on with code which you could write _once_ and put into _one_ tool.

---Dan

------------------------------

